<ns621:section xmlns:ns621="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.web.history.mosaicBrowser">
         <ns622:title xmlns:ns622="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Mosaic: The first significant web browser</ns622:title>
         <ns623:para xmlns:ns623="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
             Though the first web browser, created by Berners-Lee, was called <ns624:emphasis xmlns:ns624="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">WorldWideWeb</ns624:emphasis> 
             (later renamed to <ns625:emphasis xmlns:ns625="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Nexus</ns625:emphasis> to avoid confustion with the name for the abstract
             information space), it was the Mosaic browser which provided the first easy-to-use graphical,
             multimedia interface to the World Wide Web.
         </ns623:para>
         <ns626:para xmlns:ns626="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
             It was originally developed for the UNIX <ns627:emphasis xmlns:ns627="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">X Window System</ns627:emphasis>, but later versions were available
             for all major platforms of the day. Both Microsoft's Internet Explorer and Netscape Navigator
             had their roots in the source code of Mosaic, and it is thus to this application which can be
             attributed the success of the World Wide Web (outside of research and academic institutions).
         </ns626:para>
